  "methodology": [
    "The lesson will use demonstrations, practical exercises, and troubleshooting to teach students about borderless and reverse printing styles."
  ],
  "activities": [
    ["1", "2", "3", "4", "5"],
    [
      "<b>Part 1: Introduction to Printing Styles</b>:<br><br>Start by introducing the concept of printing styles. Explain that when we print documents or images from a computer, we can control different aspects of how the content appears on the printed page. These include elements like borders, margins, orientation, and specific printing effects.<br><br>Borderless Printing: This is a style where the printed content goes right to the edge of the page, without leaving any blank space (i.e., no margins).<br>Reverse Printing: This involves printing in reverse colors, meaning the text and images are inverted. For example, black text might print as white, and white areas may turn black.<br><br><b>Key Terms to Know</b>:<br>Border: The line or space around the content.<br>Reverse Colors: Colors that are inverted, typically used for visual effect.<br>Margins: The blank space around the content on the page.",
      "<b>Part 2: How to Apply Borderless Printing</b>:<br><br>1. Step-by-Step Instructions:<br>Open a Document/Image: Open any document or image you want to print.<br>Access Print Settings: Click the 'File' menu in most applications (like Word or an image viewer) and select 'Print'.<br>Printer Preferences: In the Print dialog box, click on 'Printer Properties' or 'Preferences.'<br>Select Borderless Printing: Look for a setting that says 'Borderless Printing' or something similar in the layout or paper settings section.<br>Set Paper Size: Ensure that you have selected the correct paper size that supports borderless printing, such as A4 or letter size.<br><br>2. Demonstration:<br>Show students how to do this on a computer, walking them through selecting the borderless option in the print settings.",
      "<b>Part 3: How to Apply Reverse Printing</b>:<br><br>1. Step-by-Step Instructions:<br>Open a Document/Image: Open the document or image that you want to print in reverse colors.<br>Access Print Settings: Click the 'File' menu and select 'Print'.<br>Printer Preferences: In the Print dialog box, click on 'Printer Properties' or 'Preferences'.<br>Select Reverse Print or Invert Colors: Some printers allow you to apply a reverse or inverted colors option directly in the settings. If not, you can achieve this effect by changing the document’s color settings in an application (e.g., turning black text into white text).<br>Test the Print: Preview the document before printing to ensure the colors appear as expected.<br><br>2. Demonstration:<br>Show the students how to enable reverse printing on a computer, demonstrating the process with both a simple text document and an image to showcase how reverse printing works.",
      "<b>Part 4: Troubleshooting and Common Issues</b>:<br><br>Explain to students some of the common issues they may encounter when using printing styles:<br><br>Paper Alignment: Make sure the paper is correctly aligned in the printer to avoid printing errors, especially when using borderless settings.<br>Printer Compatibility: Not all printers support borderless printing or reverse color printing. Discuss how to check if a printer supports these features.<br>Print Preview: Always use the print preview function before printing to save time and resources.",
      "<b>Part 5: Exercise (Practical Activity)</b>:<br><br>Instructions for the Students:<br><br>1. Task 1: Apply Borderless Printing:<br>Choose a document (or create one if necessary) and apply borderless printing using the steps you learned in Part 2.<br>Ensure the content fills the entire page, with no margins.<br><br>2. Task 2: Apply Reverse Printing:<br>Choose a document and apply reverse printing (inverted colors) as shown in Part 3.<br>Ensure that the text is inverted (white text on a black background) and any images or graphics are printed in reverse colors.<br><br>3. Task 3: Print a Test Page:<br>After applying both styles (borderless and reverse), print a test page.<br>Make sure both effects are visible in the printed document."
    ]
  ],
