  "activities": [
    ["1", "2", "3", "4", "5"],
    [
      "<b>Part 1: Introduction to Printing Styles</b>:<br><br>Printing styles refer to the settings you can apply to a document to control how it will appear when printed. These include page orientation, margins, headers, footers, font size, line spacing, etc. Today, we’ll focus on page orientation and margins.",
      "<b>Part 2: Page Orientation</b>:<br><br><b>Objective:</b> Students will learn about the two main types of page orientation used in printing.<br><br><b>Explanation:</b><br>Portrait Orientation: This is the default setting where the page is taller than it is wide. It’s commonly used for text-based documents, such as essays and reports.<br>Landscape Orientation: This orientation is where the page is wider than it is tall. It is often used for images, tables, or wide spreadsheets.<br><br>Activity:<br>Show the class how to change the page orientation in a word processing software (e.g., Microsoft Word, Google Docs).<br>Discuss when each orientation is useful.",
      "<b>Part 3: Margins in Printing</b>:<br><br><b>Objective:</b> Students will understand what margins are and how to adjust them for printing.<br><br><b>Explanation:</b><br>Margins are the blank spaces around the edges of the page, separating the text or images from the paper’s edge.<br>Common margin settings include:<br>- Normal margins (default setting)<br>- Narrow margins (less space around the edges)<br>- Wide margins (more space around the edges)<br><br>Adjusting margins helps to control how much content fits on a page and ensures that the content is properly positioned for printing.<br><br>Activity:<br>Demonstrate how to change the margins in a word processing software.<br>Explain the effect of different margin settings on the appearance of a document.",
      "<b>Part 4: Applying Printing Styles</b>:<br><br><b>Objective:</b> Students will apply page orientation and margin settings to a document.<br><br><b>Explanation:</b><br>After learning about page orientation and margins, it's important to know how to apply these settings to make the document fit the content and look organized when printed.<br><br>Changing Page Orientation: Show how to go to the 'Page Layout' or 'Layout' tab in a word processor and change the page orientation.<br>Adjusting Margins: Show how to access margin settings, and explain the difference between narrow, normal, and wide margins.<br><br>Tip: Always check the 'Print Preview' option to see how the changes will appear on the printed page.",
      "<b>Part 5: Exercise</b>:<br><br><b>Objective:</b> Students will practice applying page orientation and margin settings in a document.<br><br><b>Instructions:</b><br>1. Open a new document in a word processing software (e.g., Microsoft Word or Google Docs).<br>2. Set the page orientation to Landscape.<br>3. Adjust the margins to Narrow.<br>4. Insert a title at the top of the page (e.g., 'My First Landscape Document').<br>5. Type a paragraph of your choice, making sure the text fits well on the page without being cut off.<br><br><b>Task:</b><br>After completing the task, students will print the document to check how the page looks with the new settings.<br>Discuss the outcome in class and ask students to share their experiences with adjusting the page settings."
    ]
  ],
